:"1237","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1211":"1211","Abt 1264":"about 1264","1232":"1232","1265":"1265","about 1265":"about 1265","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, England","Klive, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hughley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hughley (Shropshire), named in Old English with the element <i>lēah</i> ‘glade or clearing in a wood’. The Middle English personal name   Hugh   was prefixed to this in the 12th century, to indicate ownership.","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Hügli</b> (see   Hugley  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Constant","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constans</i> ‘steadfast’ (genitive <i>Constantis</i>). This was not a common name in the Middle Ages, but was used particularly in the Maude family. The vernacular variant  <b>Costin</b>  is also found. The name was taken up more widely among Christians from the 17th century onwards, partly because of its transparent meaning and partly as expressing a determination to follow the exhortations of  St Peter : ‘Be sober, be vigilant; because your adversary the devil, as a roaring lion, walketh about, seeking whom he may devour; whom resist stedfast (<i>constant</i>) in the faith’ (1 Peter 5:8–9)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":22,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":53,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Constant Hughley was born in 1237, in Ashington, Somerset, England, her father, NN de Hughley, was 65 and her mother, NN de` Hughley NN, was 65. She married Sir Knight Matthew Somerset Furneaux in 1263, in Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1302, in her hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1237–1302":"1237–1302","1211–1293":"1211–1293","1264–1316":"1264–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1172–1232":"1172–1232","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1293":"1293","1172":"1172","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1211":"1211","Abt 1264":"umbes 1264","1232":"1232","1265":"1265","about 1265":"umbes 1265","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England","Ashington, Somerset, England":"Ashington, Somerset, England","Klive, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1237–1302":"1237–1302","1211–1293":"1211–1293","1264–1316":"1264–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1172–1232":"1172–1232","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1293":"1293","1172":"1172","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1237":"1237","